<br>
I think you miss the point.<br>
<br>
You are completely 100% correct that if I send you a picture, and you post it, you will *probably* not have a problem.  If I at a later time decide that I want a newer picture (I've gotten a new do - yay me!) you will replace the picture.  Or if I decide I no longer want it up for whatever reason you will take it down.  I have no doubt that you will do that.<br>
<br>
However, How can you guarentee that *I* am the person sending you the picture.  Could I make a hotmail/msn/ whatever account and pretend that I am you or anyone else for that matter? I sure can. Would you know?  Probably not.  <br>
<br>
Let's not even suppose that the person is doing it in a mean or negative way...  but say they want to help flush out the mural with their own collection of pictures.  I have pictures of many people from Lanys.  I have been to a number of lanys and guild RL functions.  I go to the EQ events.  I enjoy doing it.   I have those pictures for my own benefit.  So I email them to you - and I say yes I have permission...  because I assume that by attending a lanys function that everyone there was expecting their pictures to be taken.  But, though they might have attended that function, it does not give me a blank slate on where I can post those pictures publically.  I would be wrong.  You by default would be wrong.  You by being the owner of the mural would be legally wrong, and liable.<br>
<br>
Do I care if someone at one of the functions I attended posts my picture?  Not really.  Would anyone else?  Who knows...  but without my explicit permission to post that photo on a website, you can not do it.  It's why we in the industry use releases.<br>
<br>
Here's another issue.  It's a website.  Someone happens along and sees my picture.  They just happend to be the Insert Designer for happy tap dance picture frame company. They decide that my picture would be the perfect photo for the new line of frames coming out.  They take the picture off the mural... and I walk into Macy's and see 9,000 me's staring back.  Guess who I get to sue...  the frame company, and you.  You personally.  I might have implied my permission to be on your mural by emailing that picture to you...  but I certainly did not give my permission to be frame girl 2002.  With no release...  you screwed dude. (An actual MA case...  not only did the frame company have to pay out big but also the photo studio who sold the photo.  Not really harmless to the couple who were in the frames.... eh?)<br>
<br>
Which is why the mural though a great idea in theory, needs someone who is going to abide by the legal necessities of using peoples likenesses in a public venue.  If you're not going to...  you are *probably* going to have problems.  You might not...  but are you willing to take that risk?  <br>
<br>
